A new study shows that more people die from air pollution than malaria and HIV/AIDS
According to a new reference study, over 3 million people die prematurely each year due to air pollution from outside, more than malaria and HIV/AIDS together.
The main cause, especially in Asia, is wood and coal burned for heating houses and cooking, but research reveals that a similar alarming reason is agricultural emissions from Europe and the United States, where it is the main reason for these deaths.
The report warns that if no action is taken, the number of deaths - already equivalent to six deaths per minute - will double by 2050.
"These projections should draw an alarm signal for public health agencies around the world," said Professor Michael Jerrett, environmental health expert at the University of California, who was not involved in research.
Most of the deaths caused by air rain are caused by tiny particles, which can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
They cause stroke and stroke, which are responsible for three quarters of the 3.3 million deaths annually, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory diseases.
Research has not included the effects of indoor air pollution, e.g. from cooking fires, which are estimated to cause 3.4 million more deaths per year.
The new study, published in Nature newspaper, is the first to highlight various sources of outdoor air pollution and estimated the number of premature deaths they cause, taking into account road traffic, fossil fuel plants and other sources.
Researchers have used a detailed computerized model of the global atmosphere to assess the impact of air pollution on different populations, including new information on how pollution affects Chinese and Indian inhabitants.
One third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of smoke-extinguishing fuels, such as wood and coal, for heating houses or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of which are recognised dangers.
The consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of India’s 645 000 annual deaths and one third of China’s 1.4 million annual deaths.
However, the research found that agricultural ammonia emissions had a "remarkable" impact, according to Professor Jos Lelieveld from the German Chemical Max Planck Institute, which led the research.
A fifth of deaths at global level are caused by these emissions, which mainly come from cattle, birds and pigs and from the excess use of fertilizers.
The ammonia reacts with exhaust gases from traffic and industry and produces tiny particles, being the main reason of death due to air pollution in the east of the United States, Japan and Europe.
"For London, agriculture is the main source," says Lelieveld.
Throughout the United Kingdom, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still an important factor in developed countries, causing a fifth of deaths, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
This has caused only 5% of deaths globally, but the figure could increase as more and more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
Air pollution by the plant, in particular by those operating with coal, was significant globally, causing one of seven deaths.
In the United States, it is the main single factor, causing one third of the 55,000 deaths annually, compared with 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in arid regions and with much dust, has caused nearly a fifth of the deaths globally caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, responsible for 92% of deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
"The overlap between the high degree of pollution and the large number of residents says the word on public health, but no more is known about the sources of pollution responsible for premature deaths," says Jerrett.
The results are surprising and potentially important for overall public health protection.
Currently, all particles are assumed to be as toxic.
But if those caused by fuel burning are more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths that can be attributed to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, Jerrett says "discovery is very valuable... because agriculture has not generally been seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and because it suggests that much more attention should be paid to agricultural sources, both from scientists and political leaders."
Dr. Oliver Wild, an atmosphere specialist at Lancaster University in the United Kingdom, said: “The study really underlines the need for air quality control to avoid these deaths, especially in the very populated areas of Asia.”
