Many coral reefs, usually described as tropical forests of the oceans due to their huge biodiversity, could be threatened with extinction by the middle of this century if the acidity of the ocean continues to deteriorate, as a result of increased levels of CO2 in the atmosphere, causing direct proportional increase in the level of carbonic acid from the sea.
"Healthy seas are a source of extraordinary beauty and natural wonder and are also a basis for the functioning of the global economy," said Louise Heaps, Chief Marine Policy Adviser at WWF-UK, who contributed to the preparation of the report.
"By overfishing, which damage coastal habitats, and without solving the problem of global warming, we resemble the seeds of an ecological economic catastrophe," said Dr. Heaps.
The report, based on a review of published scientific literature, but also on the Indexes of the living planet, a database maintained by the London Zoo Society, is one of the most detailed studies on marine life ever undertaken.
Nearly 20% of the total mangrove areas disappeared between 1980 and 2005 (WWF) It investigated a great diversity of marine species, from fish, sea turtles and sea currants - an animal similar to a worm, with rough skin - up to marine plants such as mangroves and algae.
The report found that the areas of algae have decreased by about 30% in the last century, while the total number of mangrove areas has decreased by 20% between 1980 and 2005, mainly as a result of shrimp fishing and other forms of aquaculture.
During a single generation, human activity has caused enormous damage to the ocean, catching fish faster than it can reproduce and also destroying their banks.
Deep changes are needed to ensure an abundant ocean life in the next generations," said Marco Lambertini, director general of WWF International.
Some of the most dramatic declines have occurred in fishing species for commercial profits.
For example, 58 people from 17 species belonging to the Scrombodae family - macro, ton and sardines - fell by 74% between 1970 and 2010, without any signs of recovery, the report says.
We are in a fishing race that could end up depriving people of a vital food source and an essential economic engine.
Excess fishing, the destruction of marine habitats and climate change have serious consequences for the entire human population, and poor communities, which are based on the sea, will be hit the fastest and most powerful," Lambertini said.
"The collapse of ocean ecosystems could trigger a serious economic decline and could undermine our struggle to eradicate poverty and undernutrition," he continued.
Professor Ken Norris, scientific director of the ZL, said: "These alarming figures prove how quickly people change plants and animals in the ocean and represent a clear warning about the problems we may face as a result."
Sea grass: deep underwater "pastions" that catch rich sediments in minerals and stabilize the seabed.
Over the last century, the coverage area has decreased by 30%.
Mangrove: their existence is known in 123 countries, almost half of the total area representing only five countries.
Almost 20% of all mangrove areas disappeared between 1980 and 2005, mainly due to human invasion.
Coral reefs: some of the richest and most biologically productive habitats on earth.
A quarter of all marine species live in or near coral reefs, but three quarters of them are currently threatened and many can disappear during this century if ocean acid continues to deteriorate.
Deep-sea habitats: very little is known about the deeper areas of the ocean, but the decline in the amount of fish caught in these inaccessible locations over the past 40 years suggests that they are also affected by global marine changes.
