Raised, therefore, the red-burned flag/ Under his skirts we will live and die.
That's what Jeremy Corbyn sang yesterday in the London Sanctuary House pub.
He's been testifying to many facts and vows. Let's not change his color now.
Readers who don't know the song line of this unofficial British and international left (Red Flag/The Red Flag) could search the Internet and would not be excluded from being part of a surprise.
With the heads discovered, let's all swear that we'll wear it until we fall.
The author of these lines is not at all an admirer of the red flags (and not those that float them), but respects the democratic political traditions built around them.
If Jeremy Corbyn manages to join the left yesterday with the one tomorrow, this love story between him and the Labour Party base will be part of a happy-end.
I don't think it will happen that way, but it seems to me premature to talk about the great and inevitable electoral defeat, over five years, of a leader chosen yesterday.
Now, however, we can refer to procedures: we have witnessed a democratic exercise of an impressive scope.
The British workers did not invent the voting system directly for the party leader, on the western left.
French Socialists have been practicing for a few years a more complicated system, based on motions, which allows the expression of all members and supporters; in addition, they have organised a preliminary competition for the appointment of the candidate to the presidential in 2012.
However, the internal election of workers seems to be more spectacular and more politically significant, as the new leader chosen automatically becomes his head of launch in future elections.
It is, of course, also a matter of political system, personalizing power being more pronounced in Britain than the other side of the Channel of the Hand.
In addition, participation in the vote was high in all three "circulations": members themselves, members of trade unions and other organisations affiliated to the party and finally the group of supporters (who received the ballot after a summary registration procedure).
This last group gives us interesting information about the perceptions of the left segments of British society, especially those made up of young or middle-aged people, educated, interested in the political phenomenon.
Many of them will choose to involve themselves even more, in the future, just because of Corbyn's signal of victory.
There are, as far as I know, sociological investigations that tell us too much about the attitudes of this "outer circle" laborist, so careful speculation is allowed.
I think we encounter a lot of attitudes similar to those of sympathizers Podemos (Spain) or even SYRIZA (Greece), with the observation that they will travel through the traditional channels of the left.
If we have to identify a "anti-system" vocation, it is primarily reflected by rejecting the centrist line, New Labour (for many, just a dissimulated form of much-hulite thatcherism).
The second component would be the repudiation of the leaders considered guilty by the two successive electoral failures, one of the arguments being that they did not go left enough, that they did not demarcate firmly from the Tony Blair era.
The second - and more suggestive - landmark is offered by the recent referendum on independence of Scotland.
If we are abstracting from the separatist message and are focusing strictly on aspirations regarding other political themes, we see how Scottish nationalists have captured the energies of social-friendly public segments animated by the aspiration of equity, followers of disarmament and hostile military involvement across borders, but also sensitive to the new themes of the left: ecology, gender, assistance for poor countries.
Scottish workers have thus lost an electorate to which they should have, at least in principle, privileged access, but which they can now recover (see their enthusiasm for Corbyn’s campaign).
Such energy exists everywhere in the United Kingdom, but the old leadership couldn't attract them.
Jeremy Corbyn, with his vocation as an outsider, has more chance of success than Ed Miliband, the laborer's "aristocrat".
The comparison with Scotland tells us more, I think, than the one with the left antisym from the southern periphery of Europe.
The term "anti-system" is too harsh: "anti-establishment" seems more appropriate to me.
Until next week we'll learn more about Jeremy Corbyn's first steps as leader of the opposition.
We'll see if the red flag will rise in the House of Commons (it won't be for the first time), after the new leader will be taken over, first of all the opposition banks.
However, what Jeremy Corbyn now wants from his colleagues in Parliament is primarily unity - and in this regard he even has reason to be concerned.
